<paper id="1883414310"><title>Searching for the optimum correlation attack</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="Computer Laboratory" id="2120643228">Ross J. Anderson</author></authors><n_citation>66</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>118210125</reference><reference>1526777359</reference><reference>1529662056</reference><reference>1571317543</reference><reference>1587697857</reference><reference>1661175875</reference><reference>1871381818</reference><reference>1979198062</reference><reference>1979802565</reference><reference>1980279697</reference><reference>1983629106</reference><reference>2006156883</reference><reference>2007555486</reference><reference>2026522166</reference><reference>2130097310</reference><reference>2130972067</reference><reference>2154271831</reference><reference>2161517294</reference></references><venue id="2758283624" type="C">Fast Software Encryption</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-60590-8_11</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.65162">Keystream</keyword><keyword weight="0.51616">Shift register</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Linear feedback shift register</keyword><keyword weight="0.45938">Information leakage</keyword><keyword weight="0.39932">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.42971">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.55947">Stream cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Filter (function)</keyword><keyword weight="0.68283">Correlation attack</keyword><keyword weight="0.51334">Nonlinear filter</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present some new ideas on attacking stream ciphers based on regularly clocked shift registers. The nonlinear filter functions used in such systems may leak information if they interact with shifted copies of themselves, and this gives us a systematic way to search for correlations between a keystream and the underlying shift register sequence.</abstract></paper>